    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>

        <p>
            Measurement is never perfectly exact. Every measurement has a small degree of uncertainty due to limitations of measuring instruments and human factors.
        </p>
        <p>
            Differences in results may arise due to:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Different measuring instruments (resolution and size)</p> 
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Parallax error (incorrect viewing angle)</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Starting point misalignment</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Human estimation differences</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            Because of these limitations, we often give measurements as approximations rather than exact values.
        </p>

        <p>
            This leads to the idea of:
        </p>

        <p>
            <term>Absolute Error:</term> the difference between the measured value and the true value (when known).
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, repeated measurements and better instruments improve reliability but never completely remove error.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Three students measure the same desk and obtain 120 cm, 121 cm, and 119 cm. Explain why the results are not identical.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Differences occur due to measurement errors such as parallax error, instrument precision, and human reading differences.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>

        <statement>
            <p>
                A tape measure gives a more consistent result than a 15 cm ruler when measuring a desk. Explain why.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                A tape measure covers a longer distance at once, reducing repeated placements and therefore reducing cumulative error.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

